Qestion: if PodDistributionbudget is set, and due to load on worker nodes, pod eviction failes, then waht will happen, if another pods running on anothe nodes will also stop as  minAvailable is not achieved

No — existing Pods running on other healthy nodes will NOT stop automatically just because minAvailable is not achieved. Instead, Kubernetes will:

- Block further voluntary evictions.

This is the main purpose of a PodDisruptionBudget (PDB).

What PodDisruptionBudget Does

A PodDisruptionBudget protects application availability during:

1. drain
2. rolling update
3. voluntary eviction
4. maintenance

Example:

minAvailable: 2

means: At least 2 Pods must remain available.

Your Scenario: Suppose:

Deployment : 3 replicas
PDB: minAvailable: 2

Cluster
Node	     Pod
worker1	   app-pod-1
worker2	   app-pod-2
worker3	   app-pod-3

- Now Drain worker1
# kubectl drain worker1 --ignore-daemonsets

Kubernetes tries:

Evict app-pod-1
Create replacement elsewhere
Problem: Other Nodes Full

Suppose:

worker2 and worker3 have no resources
replacement Pod cannot schedule

Now cluster has:

Only 2 available Pods

which still satisfies:

minAvailable: 2

So eviction succeeds.

Now Try Another Drain

Suppose you drain worker2.

Kubernetes wants to evict:

app-pod-2

If eviction happens:

Only 1 Pod remains available

This violates:

minAvailable: 2

So Kubernetes blocks eviction.

Important Point

PDB does NOT:

kill healthy Pods
stop running Pods
shut down applications

It only:

prevents voluntary disruptions beyond limit
What Actually Happens

Drain command may hang with messages like:

Cannot evict pod as it would violate the pod's disruption budget

or:

eviction blocked by PDB
Existing Running Pods Continue Normally

Pods already running on:

worker2
worker3

continue serving traffic normally.

Kubernetes will NOT stop them just because:

minAvailable unmet
Key Concept

PDB protects against:

Voluntary disruptions

NOT:

Unexpected failures
Example of Voluntary Disruption

Protected by PDB:

kubectl drain
rolling upgrades
manual eviction
Example of Involuntary Disruption

NOT protected:

node crash
power failure
kernel panic
OOM kill
hardware failure

If two nodes crash simultaneously:

PDB cannot stop it
Why Drain Gets Stuck

Drain waits because:

eviction denied
scheduler cannot place replacement Pod
PDB rules prevent availability reduction

This is actually a protection feature.

Administrator Choices
Option 1 — Add More Capacity

Best practice.

Add worker node:

New node joins
→ replacement Pod schedules
→ drain proceeds
Option 2 — Temporarily Relax PDB

Example:

minAvailable: 1

Risk:

lower application availability
Option 3 — Force Drain (Dangerous)
kubectl drain node1 --disable-eviction

or force delete Pods.

This bypasses PDB protection and may cause outage.

